Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Hope you had a great weekend, and happy Father=E2=80=99s Day to all the Not=
 Boring dads.
This weekend, we visited my parents at the beach to celebrate Father=E2=80=
=99s Day and my dad=E2=80=99s birthday (happy birthday, dad!). On Sunday mo=
rning, my mom asked what I was writing about, and I told her I had no idea.=
 So she said, =E2=80=9COK, let=E2=80=99s brainstorm some ideas.=E2=80=9D I =
rolled my eyes, as even adult kids do when their parents make suggestions, =
but then, as parents do, she dropped wisdom:=C2=A0
We had no idea that your life was going to be what it is today when you wer=
e born. You write a newsletter, from home, and send it to people all over t=
he world, on the internet.=C2=A0
I remember when I came back from maternity leave, Donna [my mom=E2=80=99s t=
eammate at Bell Atlantic] told me about the internet for the first time. We=
 were mainly worried about coin-operated payphones at the time. We thought =
one day there would be picture phones, but we had no idea what the internet=
 would mean.
If technology is moving even faster now than it was then, imagine what the =
world is going to be like when Dev and Maya are your age. It=E2=80=99s Fath=
er=E2=80=99s Day. You should write about that.=C2=A0
Gotta hand it to her. It=E2=80=99s a good idea. After writing about a lot o=
f things that might make their future very cool over the past few weeks, th=
is is a good opportunity to look at them all together.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a shorter one (sub-2k words!) so I could spend more time with =
the kids.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
When My Kids Are My Age
The world that Dev and Maya live in when they=E2=80=99re my age is going to=
 be profoundly different than the one I grew up in or live in today. It=E2=
=80=99s impossible to predict how. I tried a little sci-fi short story [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/a634816b-b154-4452-aafe-85bd7c17ed47?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], but that=E2=80=
=99s just a guess, one of many possible futures.=C2=A0
A more useful approach might be to look at what=E2=80=99s happening right n=
ow to get a sense for just how many things are going to change. When you do=
 that, the internet looks small.=C2=A0
In just the past month, in just this newsletter, we=E2=80=99ve written piec=
es on nuclear fusion [ https://substack.com/redirect/761cf900-2fce-4db3-bbc=
6-013926e255f9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ], using screening to effectively cure cancer [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/272685a0-62cf-4718-a416-da1392a1f2f3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the intersection of blockchain an=
d biology to build new nations and grow anything we need [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/b35b50c5-8325-4374-b79=
b-68b89e1561b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and drug factories in space [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/de353a6a-a948-4935-a343-07453b254f58?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
In the Weekly Dose of Optimism, we covered quantum computing becoming usefu=
l [ https://substack.com/redirect/0944d17e-8218-479e-bda2-9a75b31ce5e4?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], spatial c=
omputing [ https://substack.com/redirect/08e72959-cc1e-45e3-bf70-7e308e9c81=
46?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], ke=
tamine for treatment-resistant major depression [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/918e55a1-9b9c-48a8-9aa3-161471eb321f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], airships and a paralyzed man walking a=
gain [ https://substack.com/redirect/dea7d963-dfbf-47d3-975d-5aebb4fce86b?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and no=
vel ways of fixing the environment [ https://substack.com/redirect/7f0cfeff=
-8b58-48a3-9ba4-2f6dc3a42dbb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
We haven=E2=80=99t even really touched on AI in the past month, but progres=
s there continues apace. Marc Andreessen has us covered with Why AI Will Sa=
ve the World [ https://substack.com/redirect/05646b33-36d3-4388-a2fe-a93d4b=
a45d80?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
=2E=C2=A0
Again, all of that (ex-Marc=E2=80=99s piece) is just what we=E2=80=99ve wri=
tten about in Not Boring from mid-May to mid-June 2023.=C2=A0
For context, when my mom got back from maternity leave, there were roughly =
30,000 hosts on the internet, and the only reason she knew it was a thing a=
t all was that she worked for a large telco. Most people had no idea what w=
as coming then, and even those who knew it was happening had no idea how it=
 would work its way into every aspect of our lives.=C2=A0
It would be presumptuous to believe that we have a clearer view of the futu=
re from our vantage point today than they did from theirs then. But there a=
re clues, even if our current cutting-edge tech is at the =E2=80=9C30,000 h=
osts on the whole internet=E2=80=9D version of what it=E2=80=99ll be in the=
 2050s, and we can extrapolate.=C2=A0
At a minimum, that famous 1954 Lawrence Strauss speech to the National Asso=
ciation of Science Writers may be true for our children even if it wasn=E2=
=80=99t for his:=C2=A0
Our children will enjoy in their homes electrical energy too cheap to meter=
=2E..will travel effortlessly over the=20=
seas and under them and through the ai=
r with a minimum of danger and at great speeds, and will experience a lifes=
pan far longer than ours, as disease yields and man comes to understand wha=
t causes him to age.
When I think about the future Dev and Maya will get to experience, I feel, =
if I=E2=80=99m being honest, a little bit jealous.=C2=A0
Even if all of the fusion companies are a decade too optimistic in their co=
mmercialization timelines [ https://substack.com/redirect/cb571fe2-d11b-442=
5-9462-2ab9a9f1ed26?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ], and commercial fusion doesn=E2=80=99t come online at meaning=
ful scale until the 2040s, Dev and Maya will already have lived with nuclea=
r fusion for a decade by the time they=E2=80=99re my age. Their generation=
=E2=80=99s entrepreneurs will get to build products with the assumption tha=
t energy is practically free.=C2=A0
Cancer, a shared nagging fear among my generation, may, for all intents and=
 purposes, be a thing of the past as the cost of screening approaches zero =
and screening technology infuses everyday products.=C2=A0
If even 10% of the biotech companies that we look at are successful, diseas=
e as we know it today may be a thing of the past. And Elliot [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/89191c94-6d26-4f76-814e-455c98a26d17?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] believes biology will be a=
ble to do a whole lot more than cure diseases. In addition to new medicines=
, he highlighted that synthetic biologists are working on growing materials=
, chemicals, and food.=C2=A0
Varda plans to send factories to space almost daily by the 2030s. What will=
 the space economy look like 20 years beyond that? Certainly, the world wil=
l be blanketed with high-speed internet connection =E2=80=93 internet too c=
heap to meter! =E2=80=93 but it=E2=80=99s not inconceivable that Dev and Ma=
ya will vacation in space hotels the way you and I might vacation in Mexico=
=2E They may even, as Robert Zubrin sug=
gests, commute to work in industrial p=
arks in space.=C2=A0
And as Marc summed up his optimistic take on AI:
In short, anything that people do with their natural intelligence today can=
 be done much better with AI, and we will be able to take on new challenges=
 that have been impossible to tackle without AI, from curing all diseases t=
o achieving interstellar travel.
Even if we=E2=80=99re at the peak of the hype cycle in any or all of these =
technologies, thirty years is enough time for them to fall into the trough =
of disillusionment, climb back up the slope of enlightenment to the plateau=
 of productivity, and become boring. My kids will be riding new S-curves we=
 can=E2=80=99t even fathom today.=C2=A0
If that seems overly optimistic, consider the fate of two technologies that=
 have been stuck in a never-ending loop in the first half of the Hype Cycle=
: AR/VR and self-driving cars.=C2=A0
AR/VR. I ranted about this on twitter [ https://substack.com/redirect/e1370=
490-8f63-4fd8-b4df-5a5d94c7111b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] already, but with Apple=E2=80=99s announcement of=
 the Vision Pro, a lot of people who were very skeptical about AR/VR a few =
weeks ago are very excited about it now. This first version won=E2=80=99t b=
e the thing that gets everyone to adopt the technology =E2=80=93 Apple proj=
ects something like 1 million units =E2=80=93 but it=E2=80=99s clear that w=
e=E2=80=99re on the path down the cost curve and up the capability curve th=
at will ultimately lead to widespread adoption.=C2=A0
Self-Driving. Right now, as we speak, in Phoenix and San Francisco, people =
can pull out their phone, book a ride with Cruise, get in a car with no dri=
ver, and get driven to their destination. There should be celebrations in t=
he streets, ticker tape parades at least as big as the Denver Nuggets=E2=80=
=99 [ https://substack.com/redirect/729d25e0-1104-4d50-8973-6524a3c1505c?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I reme=
mber watching Zenon: Girl of the 21st Century when I was twelve, seeing a b=
unch of kids hopping into a car that drove itself, and thinking that it was=
 the most futuristic, never-gonna-happen-for-real shit I=E2=80=99d ever see=
n. Twenty-four years later, we have it.=C2=A0
These breakthroughs keep happening, and each time we=E2=80=99re like, =E2=
=80=9COh yeah cool, oh well, everything still sucks.=E2=80=9D Obviously, a =
big part of the reason for that is that technology isn=E2=80=99t the cure f=
or everything, but c=E2=80=99mon. Self-driving cars are real and you can bo=
ok one on your phone. That=E2=80=99s amazing.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s this thing where some people don=E2=80=99t want to bring ch=
ildren into this terrible world of ours over fears around climate change or=
 whatever x-risk du jour terrifies them. Having kids is a choice and to eac=
h their own, but if people genuinely aren=E2=80=99t having kids because the=
y=E2=80=99re worried about climate change, that=E2=80=99s fucking tragic. T=
he kids will be alright, and if anything, our kids are going to feel bad fo=
r us for having to live in a world so primitive, like we feel bad for our g=
randparents for having to walk eight miles to and from school, in the snow,=
 uphill both ways.=C2=A0
I understand that things aren=E2=80=99t perfect today. There=E2=80=99s ineq=
uality, disease, war, homelessness, drug addiction, prejudice, and, current=
ly, this exhausting debate over the RFK Jr. debate, a little peek into our =
larger struggle with shared truths. Tech has not solved all of the world=E2=
=80=99s problems as some of its boosters have promised it would by now. But=
 the answer is not to retreat and regress; the moral imperative is to grow =
our way to the other side.
This is not pollyannaish indefinite optimism. It is definite optimism.=C2=
=A0
To be specific, the world Dev and Maya live in when they=E2=80=99re as old =
as Puja and I are now will be, conservatively, one with:=C2=A0
Cheap, abundant energy, and all of the wonderful possibilities that entails=
,=C2=A0
Fewer diseases and longer healthy lives,=C2=A0
Global connectivity for everyone on earth who wants it,
On-demand access to intelligence of all shapes and sizes,=C2=A0
More broadly distributed ownership and governance of the products we use, a=
nd better access to financial opportunity for all,
Cheaper, faster travel on earth and to space and persistent access to rich,=
 personalized and social virtual worlds,=C2=A0
Widespread availability of treatments for depression and finer tools to exp=
lore and expand the capabilities of their own minds,=C2=A0
The ability to grow an increasing percentage of the things they need biolog=
ically,
Much, much more, much of which we can=E2=80=99t possibly fathom today.=C2=
=A0
This is the world in thirty years if even a fraction of the startups today =
succeed. There will be thousands or millions of new startups formed in the =
interim, new technological breakthroughs to explore, and fascinating opport=
unities opened up as many of today=E2=80=99s moonshots become jumping-off p=
oints.=C2=A0
Just writing that list makes me so excited for Dev and Maya, and it makes m=
e want to do everything I can to help speed it up. I want them to benefit f=
rom as much of this as possible, as quickly as possible, and I want to be t=
here to help guide them through it. Selfishly, part of the reason I=E2=80=
=99m an accelerationist is that I want Puja and I to be able to live long e=
nough to experience all of this magic with them.=C2=A0
Of course, this future is not a foregone conclusion. We can easily get in o=
ur own way. There are countless paths to shooting ourselves in the foot, fr=
om getting so caught up in petty bullshit that we take our eyes off the pri=
ze to letting bad actors taint promising technologies, but those seem tract=
able. The biggest risk to this future as I see it is that we do a bad job o=
f bringing everyone along, incite backlash over every new innovation, and r=
egulate ourselves to death, at least in the United States. Nuclear [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/39b50c42-a9ef-430b-85ff-f034006629c7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and psychedelics [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/15928b43-3503-45d4-993f-94b472e40f5f?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are just two of=
 many cautionary tales.
That dynamic is the reason that Not Boring=E2=80=99s mission is to make the=
 world more optimistic. It=E2=80=99s not so that we all feel blindly and us=
elessly hopeful in the face of really bad things; it=E2=80=99s so more peop=
le can see that the future, hopefully ours and definitely our kids=E2=80=99=
, is insanely bright if we let it be, and have the knowledge and enthusiasm=
 to fight on the side of that future.=C2=A0
As I sat here writing this on Father=E2=80=99s Day, while my kids were play=
ing on the beach, I thought of the story of the investment banker and the f=
isherman [ https://substack.com/redirect/c0b6c853-d49e-4194-82a5-9e91e5aa19=
96?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Yo=
u know the story. There=E2=80=99s a fisherman who fishes a little every day=
, siestas with his wife, spends time with his kids, and dances with his fri=
ends. An investment banker vacationing in town tells him that he could fish=
 more, expand, take on financing, make a lot of money, and then retire earl=
y to fish a little every day, siesta with his wife, spend time with his kid=
s, and dance with his friends.=C2=A0
It got me. I stopped writing, went down to the beach, and played with my ki=
ds. There=E2=80=99s no point in getting excited about living longer and bei=
ng able to work less if you already don=E2=80=99t get to enjoy the time you=
 have with the people you love.=C2=A0
But they=E2=80=99re at the beach again, and I=E2=80=99m here writing. Unlik=
e the fisherman, I don=E2=80=99t want the world to look the same when I ret=
ire as it does today.
Thanks to my mom for the idea and Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/ef38c=
b38-9f2c-42f8-8802-1f02279d4ebe?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and Puja [ https://substack.com/redirect/a078e22c=
-3475-4a17-87b2-674c2f22a534?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 for the Weekly Dose.=20
Thanks for reading,
Packy

